pr_title: Calculate BAM byte ranges more accurately
pr_body:
Closes #17

Starting from what was already accomplished in #20, with some minor changes. 

I have been debugging to understand why the three ranges in the `search_reference_name_with_seq_range` get merged. It seems to me that something is wrong in the current implementation. 

In the test the content of block_ranges (which should contain where the blocks start and end) is the following:
```
[htsget-search/src/htsget/bam_search.rs:44] block_ranges = {
    1590681: 1912645,
    555224: 627987,
    1065952: 1350270,
    977196: 1065952,
    499249: 555224,
    1350270: 1454565,
    1912645: 2060795,
    256721: 499249,
    4668: 256721,
    627987: 824361,
    2060795: 2112141,
    824361: 977196,
    1454565: 1590681,
}
```
We can see  824361 is linked to 977196. If I understand correctly, that means what is between those numbers is a block. 

In the second range, the start of the chunk (`chunk.start().compressed()`) is 824361, but the end of the chunk is also 824361, so I think it should cover from 824361 to 977196, which is what the block appears to be in the hashmap. The problem I see is that when we add MAX_BLOCK_SIZE, we don't really get to the end of the block, instead we stop at 889897.

I'm still not sure what's wrong, but either the contents of the hashmap or the MAX_BLOCK_SIZE is wrong, unless we are talking about different block types. Tomorrow I will keep reading the noodles documentation to see if I can understand the error.

pr_body:
Closes #36 

When this PR is finished, the htsget-http crate will be able to receive and respond http requests following the [htsget specs](https://samtools.github.io/hts-specs/htsget.html#get-request). Presumably the first implementation will be kept simple and further iterations will be needed to cover all the specs.

pr_body:
Closes #10 

Adds a HtsGetIdResolver trait and a RegexResolver that implements it using regular expressions
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 689458470, 'comment_body': 'It's good to have the general idea on how to match with regexes, but I think that it could be more appropriate to have a particular example that targets particular files, as the reference impl does in:

https://github.com/ga4gh/htsget-refserver#configuration---reads-object

i.e:

```
                "sources": [
                    {
                        "pattern": "^tabulamuris\\.(?P<accession>10X.*)$",
                        "path": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/czbiohub-tabula-muris/10x_bam_files/{accession}_possorted_genome.bam"
                    },
                    {
                        "pattern": "^tabulamuris\\.(?P<accession>.*)$",
                        "path": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/czbiohub-tabula-muris/facs_bam_files/{accession}.mus.Aligned.out.sorted.bam"
                    }
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 16, 11, 35, 9, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'brainstorm', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 689459896, 'comment_body': 'You mean default substitution? IIRC regexes for `sed` have `'s'` for "substitution", minor detail. ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 16, 11, 37, 40, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'brainstorm', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 689460687, 'comment_body': 'Aha, I see now, `HTSGET_MATCH` & `HTSGET_SUBSTITUTION`... perhaps even with `_REGEX_` in the middle to make it more explicit? It took me a bit longer to grasp what it meant otherwise.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 16, 11, 39, 5, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'brainstorm', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 689460942, 'comment_body': "I'd remove this reference to the regex crate if it doesn't have a link.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 16, 11, 39, 30, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'brainstorm', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 690228574, 'comment_body': 'I think I have also seen replacement, but yeah, substitution is more common', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 17, 10, 11, 24, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'CastilloDel', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 690229692, 'comment_body': 'Yeah, it is probably better that way üëçüèª ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 17, 10, 12, 55, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'CastilloDel', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 690230187, 'comment_body': 'I think I wanted to add the link later and then forgot about it üò• I will add it', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 17, 10, 13, 43, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'CastilloDel', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 693393039, 'comment_body': "I have tried to come up with a better example, but I haven't find anything that satisfies me. Could you give me a hint on what exactly would be okay? My original intent was to show the use of capture groups", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 21, 19, 38, 49, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'CastilloDel', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 693693676, 'comment_body': 'If you visit https://s3.amazonaws.com/czbiohub-tabula-muris/, take a look at the example data files that sit there and imagine that you [only want to expose samples sequenced by 10X technology](https://www.10xgenomics.com/) as "sources" of data, that could be a good documentation example and it's very similar to what htsget-refserver from GA4GH does above :)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 23, 6, 28, 20, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'brainstorm', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 694025939, 'comment_body': "Hmm, but we don't have that type of storage right now. Wouldn't an example like that be a little confusing?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 23, 14, 30, 24, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'CastilloDel', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 694391114, 'comment_body': 'Ooh, you are totally right, we only have "local" and the "S3" storage backend that @mmalenic is working on right now. Ok, leave it as-is for now, fix the conflicts and merge, we'll rephrase/update when we get the appropriate (http?) storage backend.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 24, 0, 14, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'brainstorm', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 694724645, 'comment_body': 'Okay!
